# <span id="ii-p2.1"></span><span id="ii-p2.2"></span>INTRODUCTION.

<span id="ii-p3"></span>

<span id="ii-p4"></span>

<span id="ii-p5"></span><span id="ii-p5.1"></span>THE present volume of
<span id="ii-p5.2"></span>St. Anselm’s<span id="ii-p5.3"></span> most
important philosophical and theological writings contains: (1) The
*Proslogium* (2) the *Monologium*, (3) the *Cur Deus Homo*, and (4) by
way of historical complement, an Appendix to the *Monologium* entitled
<span id="ii-p5.4"></span>In Behalf of the Fool<span
id="ii-p5.5"></span> by <span id="ii-p5.6"></span>Gaunilon<span
id="ii-p5.7"></span>, a monk of Marmoutiers. The *Proslogium* (which,
though subsequent in point of time to the *Monologium*, is here placed
first, as containing the famous ontological argument), the *Monologium*
and the Appendix thereto were translated by <span
id="ii-p5.8"></span>Mr. Sidney Norton Deane<span id="ii-p5.9"></span>,
of New Haven, Conn.; the <span id="ii-p5.10"></span>Cur Deus Homo<span
id="ii-p5.11"></span> was rendered by <span id="ii-p5.12"></span>James
Gardiner Vose<span id="ii-p5.13"></span>, formerly of Milton, Conn., and
later of Providence, R. I., and published in 1854 and 1855 in the <span
id="ii-p5.14"></span>Bibliotheca Sacra<span id="ii-p5.15"></span>, then
issued at Andover, Mass., by <span id="ii-p5.16"></span>Warren F.
Draper<span id="ii-p5.17"></span>. The thanks of the reading public are
due to all these gentlemen for their gratuitous labors in behalf of
philosophy.

<span id="ii-p6"></span><span id="ii-p6.1"></span>Welch’s recent book
<span id="ii-p6.2"></span>Anselm and His Work, by its accessibility,
renders any extended biographical notice of <span
id="ii-p6.3"></span>Anselm unneccessary. We append, therefore, merely a
few brief paragraphs from <span id="ii-p6.4"></span>Weber’s admirable
<span id="ii-p6.5"></span>History of Philosophy on <span
id="ii-p6.6"></span>Anselm’s position in the world of thought, and we
afterwards add (this, at the suggestion of <span
id="ii-p6.7"></span>Prof. George M. Duncan, of Yale University) a series
of quotations regarding <span id="ii-p6.8"></span>Anselm’s most
characteristic contribution to philosophy ‑‑*the ontological argument*
‑‑from <span id="ii-p6.9"></span>Descartes, <span
id="ii-p6.10"></span>Spinoza, <span id="ii-p6.11"></span>Locke, <span
id="ii-p6.12"></span>Leibnitz, <span id="ii-p6.13"></span>Kant, <span
id="ii-p6.14"></span>Hegel, <span id="ii-p6.15"></span>Dorner, <span
id="ii-p6.16"></span>Lotze, and <span id="ii-p6.17"></span>Professor
Flint. A bibliography also has been compiled. Thus the work will give
full material and indications for the original study of one of the
greatest exponents of Christian doctrine.

